    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Steel rebar, or reinforcement, is added to concrete foundations to enhance their overall strength and durability. This is because concrete's compressive strength far exceeds its tensile strength. In other words, concrete can withstand vertical stresses (compression) extremely well, but it can't resist horizontal stresses (tension) as well. When steel rebar is embedded within the concrete, it helps distribute tensile forces more evenly, preventing the concrete from cracking under stress.",
      "source": "target",
